 personal recollections by son Paul Malamud, memoirs and portraits by good friends, colleagues, and fellow writers such as Cynthia Ozick, Daniel Stern, and Nicolas Delbanco illuminate Malamud's life and work. The contributors reveal that in an age that deconstructs, Malamud's voice does not. Instead, it speaks clearly and imaginatively with the weight of ancient traditions and the understanding of modern conditions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aHumanism in literature. 0aJewish authorszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aJewish fictionxHistory and criticism. 0aJews in literature. 0aJewszUnited StatesxIntellectual life. 0aJudaism and literaturezUnited States. 0aNovelists, Americany20th centuryvBiography. 4aLiterature : American Literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Jewish.2bisacsh1 aAarons, Victoria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAbramson, Edward A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAvery, Evelyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAvery, Evelyn, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCheuse, Alan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDelbanco, Nicholas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKremer, S. Lillian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMalamud, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMesher, D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOzick, Cynthia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPinsker, Sanford, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPolster, Karen L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSalzberg, Joel, econtributo